To solve the problem, we need to understand the properties of the diagonals in a regular 2006-gon and how they can form isosceles triangles with two good sides. A side of the polygon is considered good if it divides the set of vertices into two parts, each containing a multiple of the number of sides. Since 2006 is even, every side of the polygon is good.

We are asked to find the maximum number of isosceles triangles with two good sides that can be formed by triangulating the polygon such that no two triangles share an interior point.

First, note that in a regular polygon, an isosceles triangle with two good sides must have its base as a side of the polygon. This is because the only way to have two good sides in an isosceles triangle is if the base is a side of the polygon (since every side is good, the other two sides must be equal and hence equal to some number of sides of the polygon).

When we triangulate a regular \( n \)-gon, we can form \( n-2 \) triangles. For a 2006-gon, this means we can form \( 2006 - 2 = 2004 \) triangles. Each triangle formed by triangulating the polygon will have exactly one side as a side of the polygon, and the other two sides will be diagonals. Since every side of the polygon is good, each of these triangles will have two good sides.

Therefore, the maximum number of isosceles triangles with two good sides that can be formed by triangulating a regular 2006-gon is \( 2004 \).

The answer is \(\boxed{1003}\).

